      "description": "The snare sound on \"Schizophrenia\" is the cutting, mid-heavy crack of a budget steel-shell drum recorded in a small Brazilian studio with limited microphone options. Steel was almost certainly the shell material — wood snares of the late 1980s were typically more expensive, and the cutting attack required to compete with two guitars and a bass through cassette-era playback systems demanded the brightness that steel shells deliver naturally.\n\nWhether the drum was 14\" x 5.5\" or 14\" x 6.5\" is unconfirmed. Both depths were common on budget steel snares of the era. The 5.5\" depth would have given the recording a slightly tighter, more cutting character; the 6.5\" depth would have added more body. Listening to the album, the snare sits in a high-mid pocket that suggests tight tuning regardless of depth — that focused, aggressive crack is the priority.\n\nJG Recording Studio in Belo Horizonte was not Morrisound. The microphone selection, the room acoustics, the available outboard gear — all of it was modest. What you hear on \"Schizophrenia\" is largely what Igor's snare sounded like in the room: a tight, mid-forward attack with minimal processing. There is no parallel compression chain, no Solid State Logic console magic, no Scott Burns-level engineering refinement. The drum cracks because it was tuned to crack and recorded without much in the way of tone-shaping intervention.\n\nIgor's tuning approach on \"Schizophrenia\" can be reconstructed by ear: high tension on the batter head, tight snare wires, minimal damping. This is the configuration that produces maximum cut in a budget recording environment. It is also the configuration that a 17-year-old self-taught drummer would naturally arrive at — crank everything tight, hit hard, let the drum scream.\n\nWhat is striking about the \"Schizophrenia\" snare sound, in retrospect, is how much of the eventual Sepultura snare DNA is already present. The cutting attack, the high-mid emphasis, the willingness to let the drum sound aggressive rather than polished — all of it foreshadows the \"Beneath the Remains\" and \"Arise\" snare tones that Scott Burns would later refine at Morrisound.",
