      "description": "This is the section where honesty matters most. Sepultura could not afford pro-line Paiste 2002, Zildjian A, or Sabian AA cymbals in 1987. The band's entire recording budget for \"Schizophrenia\" was modest by any standard, and the cymbal selection reflected that reality. Period evidence points to budget unbranded cymbals, possibly some low-end Zildjian or Paiste student-line pieces, but no specific models can be reliably confirmed.\n\nThe cassette-budget recording of the era reflected the cymbal quality directly. Listen to \"Schizophrenia\" and the cymbal sound is dry, mid-heavy, and lacking the wash and sustain of pro-line bronze. This is not a criticism of Igor's playing — it is a documentation of what budget cymbals sound like when captured in a small Brazilian studio with limited microphone options. The hi-hats sit in a tight, choked-sounding pocket. The crashes feel short and abrupt rather than expansive. The ride, where you can hear it, is more a textural element than a bell-focused voice.\n\nWhat this means for the listener is that the cymbal work on \"Schizophrenia\" reads as raw and aggressive almost by accident — the budget gear contributed to the album's aesthetic in ways that more expensive cymbals could not have replicated. When Sepultura later moved to Paiste 2002 series cymbals for \"Beneath the Remains\" and beyond, the contrast was immediate. Those cymbals open up, project, sing. The \"Schizophrenia\" cymbals do their job and step out of the way.\n\nWe are not going to list specific cymbal models here. To do so would be to fabricate detail that the historical record does not support. What we can say with confidence is this: the cymbals were budget, they were probably unbranded or low-line variants of established brands, and they sounded the way they sounded because that was what was available to a 17-year-old drummer in an independent Brazilian metal band in 1987.",
