      "description": "The snare on \"Arise\" is arguably Igor Cavalera's finest studio snare tone — a cutting, authoritative crack that sits perfectly in Scott Burns' dense mix. The steel shell delivers the brightness and projection that thrash metal demands while providing enough body to support the album's faster, more intense passages.\n\nThe 6.5\" depth gives the drum substantial presence: this is not a thin, high-pitched snare that gets lost in the guitars. Every backbeat commands attention. On the militaristic sections, like the verse of the title track, each hit lands with ceremonial precision. On the blasting passages, the snare cuts through the wall of guitar with unwavering clarity.\n\nBurns' approach to miking the snare was consistent with his Morrisound philosophy: close-mic it to capture every nuance of the attack, and let the natural character of the drum speak. The steel shell's inherent brightness meant less EQ was needed to achieve the cutting tone — Burns could focus on capturing the performance rather than sculpting the sound artificially.\n\nIgor tuned the snare tight for \"Arise\" — tighter than the medium-high tuning he would adopt for the more groove-oriented \"Chaos A.D.\" sessions. This choice prioritized articulation at extreme speeds: at the tempos required for \"Dead Embryonic Cells\" or \"Subtraction,\" the head tension needed to be high enough that the drum could respond cleanly to rapid strokes without the pitch dropping between hits.",
