      "description": "For \"Arise,\" Igor Cavalera moved to Zildjian cymbals — specifically the A Series, which had been a staple of aggressive drumming for decades. The A Series' bright, cutting tone was well suited to Morrisound's recording environment, where the cymbals needed to slice through dense multi-tracked guitars without becoming harsh or brittle.\n\nThe 14\" Heavy Hi-Hats drive the majority of \"Arise\" with relentless precision. Throughout the album's fastest sections, Igor maintains 16th-note patterns on the hi-hat while his feet execute complex double-bass figures beneath — a coordination feat that demands not just technique but significant physical conditioning. The Heavy model provides the resistance and projection needed at these tempos.\n\nThe crash cymbal pairing — 16\" and 18\" — gave Igor options for different dynamic contexts. The 16\" responds instantly and decays quickly, perfect for the rapid punctuation between riffs. The 18\" has more body and sustain, suited for the bigger moments where the entire band explodes simultaneously. Both were positioned for fast access, reflecting the rapid-fire crash demands of thrash composition.\n\nThe A 20\" Ride's clear bell articulation is audible throughout \"Arise\" in passages where Igor shifts from hi-hat driving to ride accenting. The bell cuts through even the densest guitar sections, making it a useful voice for defining beat one in complex riff structures.\n\nThe 18\" China cymbal remains a signature element of the Sepultura sound. Its trashy, immediate decay creates explosive punctuation at riff transitions — an effect that Scott Burns captured with close miking to maximize the china's aggressive character without allowing it to wash over the mix.",
